<h2>What Is the PREVENT Score?</h2>
<p>Introduced as a modern alternative to the traditional Pooled Cohort Equations (PCE), the <strong>PREVENT (Predicting Risk of CVD EVENTs) Score</strong> is the American Heart Association's latest standard for evaluating heart health in adults aged 30 to 79 who do not already have diagnosed heart disease.</p>
<p>By looking beyond basic cholesterol levels, it provides a comprehensive view of a patient's cardiovascular-kidney-metabolic (CKM) health — estimating your likelihood of a major cardiovascular event over both a <strong>10-year and 30-year</strong> span.</p>
 
<h2>What Makes PREVENT Different?</h2>
<p>The older PCE model was widely criticised for overestimating risk in some populations and lacking data for younger or highly diverse demographics. The PREVENT equations improve upon these limitations in four key ways:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Race-Free Calculation</strong> — The algorithm removes race as a biological predictor, calculating risk more equitably across all demographic groups.</li>
  <li><strong>Includes Kidney Health</strong> — It measures the kidneys' estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR), acknowledging the strong link between chronic kidney disease and heart disease.</li>
  <li><strong>Adds Heart Failure Prediction</strong> — Unlike older calculators, it predicts the risk of heart failure alongside stroke and heart attacks (ASCVD).</li>
  <li><strong>Factors in Social Disadvantage</strong> — It incorporates place-based social determinants of health, such as access to healthcare and socioeconomic barriers, which directly impact heart health.</li>
</ul>
 
<h2>How Are the Results Interpreted?</h2>
<p>The 10-year ASCVD risk categories are interpreted as follows:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Low Risk</strong> — Less than 3%</li>
  <li><strong>Borderline Risk</strong> — 3% to less than 5%</li>
  <li><strong>Intermediate Risk</strong> — 5% to less than 10%</li>
  <li><strong>High Risk</strong> — 10% or above</li>
</ul>
<p>For patients in the Intermediate or High Risk categories, doctors often recommend lifestyle modifications alongside targeted preventive therapies — such as lipid-lowering agents or blood pressure management.</p>
 
<h2>Why It Matters</h2>
<p>Because the PREVENT Score includes young adults starting at age 30, it allows patients and doctors to establish preventative strategies long before irreversible arterial damage occurs. Using the <a href="https://professional.heart.org/en/guidelines-and-statements/prevent-calculator" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--accent)">AHA PREVENT Online Calculator</a>, physicians can catch risk factors much earlier in life.</p>
<p>The inclusion of kidney function and social determinants also means the score paints a far more honest picture of a patient's real-world cardiovascular risk — not just their lab numbers in isolation.</p>
 
<h2>Key Risk Factors to Know</h2>
<p>To calculate your own PREVENT Score, your doctor will typically need:</p>
